In the deterministic selection algorithm, the input elements are divided into groups of         |
5 and calculate the median of each group. What are the complexities if the input elements       |
are divided into:                                                                               |
a. Groups of 7.                                                                                 |
b. Groups of 3.                                                                                 |
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The original algorithm (groups of 5) has recurrence: T(n)≤T(n/5)+T(7n/10)+O(n)T(n) \le T(n/5) + T(7n/10) + O(n).
The reason: the median-of-medians guarantees at least 3n/10 elements on each side → recursion goes into at most 7n/10 elements.

a. Groups of 7
Each group of 7 elements: the median guarantees at least 4 out of 7 elements are ≥ or ≤ the median-of-medians.
Elements eliminated per step: at least 4×⌈n/7⌉/2≈2n/7. Recursion into at most n−2n/7=5n/7.

T(n)≤T(⌈n/7⌉)+T(5n/7)+O(n)

Check: 1/7+5/7=6/7<11/7 + 5/7 = 6/7 < 1
1/7+5/7=6/7<1 → converges → T(n) = O(n) 
However, the constant factor is larger than groups of 5 (bigger groups cost more to find each median).

b. Groups of 3
Each group of 3 elements: the median guarantees at least ⌈n/3⌉×1\lceil n/3 \rceil \times 1
⌈n/3⌉×1 element eliminated per side → recursion into at most n−2×n/6=2n/3.

T(n)≤T(⌈n/3⌉)+T(2n/3)+O(n)

Check: 1/3+2/3=11/3 + 2/3 = 1 → does not converge!
When the sum equals 1, this recurrence yields T(n) = O(n log n) — no longer linear. This is why groups of 3 are insufficient.

